    <details>
        <summary>
        function | <a name='data/input/tseries/util_feat.py:pd_colcat_tonum' href='https://github.com/arita37/dsa2/tree/multi/data/input/tseries/util_feat.py#L619'>pd_colcat_tonum</a>
        </summary>
        <ul>
        <li>Args:</li>
        <ul>df,<br>colcat = "all",<br>drop_single_label = False,<br>drop_fact_dict = True,<br></ul>
        <li>Docs:<br>    """
<br>
    Encoding a data-set with mixed data (numerical and categorical) to a numerical-only data-set,
<br>
    using the following logic:
<br>
    * categorical with only a single value will be marked as zero (or dropped, if requested)
<br>
    * categorical with two values will be replaced with the result of Pandas `factorize`
<br>
    * categorical with more than two values will be replaced with the result of Pandas `get_dummies`
<br>
    * numerical columns will not be modified
<br>
    **Returns:** DataFrame or (DataFrame, dict). If `drop_fact_dict` is True, returns the encoded DataFrame.
<br>
    else, returns a tuple of the encoded DataFrame and dictionary, where each key is a two-value column, and the
<br>
    value is the original labels, as supplied by Pandas `factorize`. Will be empty if no two-value columns are
<br>
    present in the data-set
<br>
    Parameters
<br>
    ----------
<br>
    df : NumPy ndarray / Pandas DataFrame
<br>
        The data-set to encode
<br>
    colcat : sequence / string
<br>
        A sequence of the nominal (categorical) columns in the dataset. If string, must be 'all' to state that
<br>
        all columns are nominal. If None, nothing happens. Default: 'all'
<br>
    drop_single_label : Boolean, default = False
<br>
        If True, nominal columns with a only a single value will be dropped.
<br>
    drop_fact_dict : Boolean, default = True
<br>
        If True, the return value will be the encoded DataFrame alone. If False, it will be a tuple of
<br>
        the DataFrame and the dictionary of the binary factorization (originating from pd.factorize)
<br>
    """
<br>
</li>
        </ul>
    </details>

<br>
            the keys are the modality names.  (Default: `None`)
<br>
        batch_size : int, optional
<br>
            The number of samples used to calculate a gradient update.  If

        epochs : int, optional
<br>
            Number of epochs to train.  (Default: 1)
<br>
        verbose : int, optional
<br>
            Verbosity mode.  One of 0, 1 or 2.  (Default: 1)
<br>

<br>
            Callbacks to be called during training.  (Default: `None`)
<br>
        validation_split : float, optional
<br>
            The fraction as a value between 0 and 1 of `data` to be used as
<br>
            validation data.  (Default: 0.0)
<br>

            (one for each modality) or a dict with NumPy arrays as values where
<br>
            the keys are the modality names.  (Default: `None`)
<br>
        shuffle : bool or str, optional
<br>
            If true then the samples are shuffled before each epoch.  If set to
<br>
            the string 'batch' then samples are shuffled in chunks of
<br>
            `batch_size`.  (Default: `True`)
<br>
        sample_weight : array_like, optional
<br>
            Array of values for each sample in `data` to weight the loss
<br>
            function for the corresponding sample.  (Default: `None`)

        validation_sample_weight : array_like, optional
<br>
            Array of values for each sample in `validation_data` to weight the

        initial_epoch : int, optional

            The epoch index at which to start training.  (Default: 0)

            The number of batches used per epoch.  (Default: `None`)

        validation_steps : int, optional

<br>
        Returns

        -------

        history : Keras history

        </summary>
        <ul>
        <li>Args:</li>
        <ul>S,<br>num_factors,<br>lambda_reg = 1e-5,<br>num_iterations = 20,<br>init_std = 0.01,<br>verbose = False,<br>dtype = 'float32',<br>recompute_factors = recompute_factors,<br>*args,<br>**kwargs,<br></ul>
        <li>Docs:<br>    """
<br>
    factorize a given sparse matrix using the Weighted Matrix Factorization algorithm by
<br>
    Hu, Koren and Volinsky.
<br>
    S: 'surplus' confidence matrix, i.e. C - I where C is the matrix with confidence weights.
<br>
        S is sparse while C is not (and the sparsity pattern of S is the same as that of
<br>
        the preference matrix, so it doesn't need to be specified separately).
<br>
    num_factors: the number of factors.
<br>
    lambda_reg: the value of the regularization constant.
<br>
    num_iterations: the number of iterations to run the algorithm for. Each iteration consists
<br>
        of two steps, one to recompute U given V, and one to recompute V given U.
<br>
    init_std: the standard deviation of the Gaussian with which V is initialized.
<br>
    verbose: print a bunch of stuff during training, including timing information.
<br>
    dtype: the dtype of the resulting factor matrices. Using single precision is recommended,
<br>
        it speeds things up a bit.
<br>
    recompute_factors: helper function that implements the inner loop.
<br>
    returns:
<br>
        U, V: factor matrices. If bias=True, the last columns of the matrices contain the biases.
<br>
    """
<br>

import pandas as pd

def date_transform:
<br>
	df=pd.read_csv('calendar.csv')
<br>
	df['date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['date'])
<br>
	df['year'] = df['date'].dt.year
<br>
	df['month'] = df['date'].dt.month
<br>
	df['week'] = df['date'].dt.week
<br>
	df['day'] = df['date'].dt.day
<br>
	df['dayofweek'] = df['date'].dt.dayofweek
<br>
	date_cols=df[['wday','month','year','week','day']]
<br>
	scaler = MinMaxScaler(feature_range=(-0.5,0.5))
<br>
	scaler.fit(date_cols)
<br>
	transformed=scaler.transform(date_cols)
<br>
	new_df=pd.DataFrame(transformed,columns=date_cols.columns)
<br>
	embeded=df[['event_name_1','event_type_1','event_name_2','event_type_2']]
<br>
	unique=embeded['event_name_1'].unique()
<br>
	unique_vals=np.append(unique,embeded['event_name_2'].unique())
<br>
	event=pd.DataFrame(unique_vals,)
<br>
	array_nm=event['event'].unique()
<br>
	list_array=str(list(array_nm))
<br>
	vocab_size = 100
<br>
	encoded_docs = [one_hot(d, vocab_size) for d in list_array]
<br>
	max_length = 4
<br>
	padded_docs1 = pad_sequences(encoded_docs, maxlen=max_length, padding='post')
<br>
	unique=embeded['event_type_1'].unique()
<br>
	unique_vals=np.append(unique,embeded['event_type_2'].unique())
<br>
	event=pd.DataFrame(unique_vals,)
<br>
	array_nm=event['event'].unique()
<br>
	list_array=str(list(array_nm))
<br>
	vocab_size = 100
<br>
	encoded_docs = [one_hot(d, vocab_size) for d in list_array]
<br>
	max_length = 4
<br>
	padded_docs2 = pad_sequences(encoded_docs, maxlen=max_length, padding='post')
<br>
	values=df[df['snap_CA','snap_TX']]
<br>
	return new_df,padded_docs1,padded_docs2,values
<br>
def sales:
<br>
	sales=pd.read_csv('sell_prices.csv')
<br>
	sales['dept_id']=str(sales['item_id'])
<br>
	def remove(x):
<br>
    	value=x.split('_')
<br>
   	    dept=value[0]+"_"+value[1]
<br>
    	return dept
<br>
    sales['dept']=sales['item_id'].apply(remove)
<br>
    price_sum=pd.DataFrame(sales.groupby('wm_yr_wk')['sell_price'].sum())
<br>
    scaler = MinMaxScaler()
<br>
    scaler.fit(price_sum)
<br>
    price_sum['normalized']=scaler.transform(price_sum)
<br>
    x=pd.DataFrame(sales.groupby('dept')['sell_price'].unique())
<br>
	x.reset_index(inplace=True)
<br>
	def recive(v):
<br>
    	sum=0
<br>
    	for i in v:
<br>
        sum+=i
<br>
    	return round(sum,2)
<br>

<br>
	x['summed']=x['sell_price'].apply(recive)
<br>
	scaler = MinMaxScaler()
<br>
	x.set_index(keys='dept',inplace=True)
<br>
	x.drop('sell_price',inplace=True,axis=1)
<br>
	scaler.fit(x)
<br>
	x['transformed']=scaler.transform(x)
<br>
	return price_sum,x
<br>
def sales_validation:
<br>
	sales_eval=pd.read_csv('sales_train_validation.csv')
<br>
	TARGET='sales'
<br>
	index_columns = ['id','item_id','dept_id','cat_id','store_id','state_id']
<br>
	sales_eval = pd.melt(sales_eval,id_vars = index_columns,var_name = 'd',value_name = TARGET)
<br>
	temp_df = sales_eval[['id','d',TARGET]]
<br>
	#lag=1
<br>
	i=1
<br>
	print('Shifting:', i)
<br>
	temp_df['lag_'+str(i)] = temp_df.groupby(['id'])[TARGET].transform(lambda x: x.shift(i))
<br>
	#Moving avg=(7,28)
<br>
	temp_df1 = sales_eval[['id','d','sales']]
<br>
	for i in [7,28]:
<br>
    	print('Rolling period:', i)
<br>
    	temp_df['rolling_mean_'+str(i)] = temp_df1.groupby(['id'])[TARGET].transform(lambda x: x.shift(1).rolling(i).mean())
<br>
    	temp_df['rolling_std_'+str(i)]  = temp_df1.groupby(['id'])[TARGET].transform(lambda x: x.shift(1).rolling(i).std())
<br>
    	return temp_df
<br>
'''
<br>
</li>
        </ul>

        </summary>

        <li>Docs:<br>    """
<br>
        https://github.com/NTMC-Community/MatchZoo-py/blob/master/matchzoo/trainers/trainer.py#L341
<br>

<br>
       Trainer:
<br>
        def predict(
<br>
        self,
<br>
        dataloader: DataLoader
<br>
    ) -> np.array:
<br>
        
<br>
        Generate output predictions for the input samples.
<br>
        dataloader: input DataLoader
<br>
        :return: predictions
<br>
    
<br>
        with torch.no_grad():
<br>
            self._model.eval()
<br>
            predictions = []
<br>
            for batch in dataloader:
<br>
                inputs = batch[0]
<br>
                outputs = self._model(inputs).detach().cpu()
<br>
                predictions.append(outputs)
<br>
            self._model.train()
<br>
            return torch.cat(predictions, dim=0).numpy()
<br>

<br>
    """
<br>

        <ul>

        <ul>x,<br>y,<br></ul>
        <li>Docs:<br>    """
<br>
    Calculates Cramer's V statistic for categorical-categorical association.
<br>
    Uses correction from Bergsma and Wicher, Journal of the Korean Statistical Society 42 (2013):
<br>
    This is a symmetric coefficient: V(x,y) = V(y,x)
<br>
    Original function taken from: https://stackoverflow.com/a/46498792/5863503
<br>
    Wikipedia: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cram%C3%A9r%27s_V
<br>
    **Returns:** float in the range of [0,1]
<br>
    Parameters
<br>
    ----------
<br>
    x : list / NumPy ndarray / Pandas Series
<br>
        A sequence of categorical measurements
<br>
    y : list / NumPy ndarray / Pandas Series
<br>
        A sequence of categorical measurements
<br>
    """
<br>

    <details>
        <summary>
        function | <a name='source/utils/util_stat.py:np_correl_cat_cat_theils_u' href='https://github.com/arita37/dsa2/tree/multi/source/utils/util_stat.py#L100'>np_correl_cat_cat_theils_u</a>
        </summary>
        <ul>
        <li>Args:</li>
        <ul>x,<br>y,<br></ul>
        <li>Docs:<br>    """
<br>
    Calculates Theil's U statistic (Uncertainty coefficient) for categorical-categorical association.
<br>
    This is the uncertainty of x given y: value is on the range of [0,1] - where 0 means y provides no information about
<br>
    x, and 1 means y provides full information about x.
<br>
    This is an asymmetric coefficient: U(x,y) != U(y,x)
<br>
    Wikipedia: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Uncertainty_coefficient
<br>
    **Returns:** float in the range of [0,1]
<br>
    Parameters
<br>
    ----------
<br>
    x : list / NumPy ndarray / Pandas Series
<br>
        A sequence of categorical measurements
<br>
    y : list / NumPy ndarray / Pandas Series
<br>
        A sequence of categorical measurements
<br>
    """
<br>

    <details>
        <summary>
        function | <a name='source/utils/util_stat.py:np_correl_cat_num_ratio' href='https://github.com/arita37/dsa2/tree/multi/source/utils/util_stat.py#L125'>np_correl_cat_num_ratio</a>
        </summary>
        <ul>
        <li>Args:</li>
        <ul>cat_array,<br>num_array,<br></ul>
        <li>Docs:<br>    """
<br>
    Calculates the Correlation Ratio (sometimes marked by the greek letter Eta) for categorical-continuous association.
<br>
    Answers the question - given a continuous value of a measurement, is it possible to know which category is it
<br>
    associated with?
<br>
    Value is in the range [0,1], where 0 means a category cannot be determined by a continuous measurement, and 1 means
<br>
    a category can be determined with absolute certainty.
<br>
    Wikipedia: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Correlation_ratio
<br>
    **Returns:** float in the range of [0,1]
<br>
    Parameters
<br>
    ----------
<br>
    cat_array : list / NumPy ndarray / Pandas Series   A sequence of categorical measurements
<br>
    num_array : list / NumPy ndarray / Pandas Series  A sequence of continuous measurements
<br>
    """
<br>

    <details>
        <summary>
        function | <a name='source/utils/util_stat.py:pd_num_correl_associations' href='https://github.com/arita37/dsa2/tree/multi/source/utils/util_stat.py#L159'>pd_num_correl_associations</a>
        </summary>
        <ul>
        <li>Args:</li>
        <ul>df,<br>colcat = None,<br>mark_columns = False,<br>theil_u = False,<br>plot = True,<br>return_results = False,<br>**kwargs,<br></ul>
        <li>Docs:<br>    """
<br>
    Calculate the correlation/strength-of-association of features in data-set with both categorical (eda_tools) and
<br>
    continuous features using:
<br>
     * Pearson's R for continuous-continuous cases
<br>
     * Correlation Ratio for categorical-continuous cases
<br>
     * Cramer's V or Theil's U for categorical-categorical cases
<br>
    **Returns:** a DataFrame of the correlation/strength-of-association between all features
<br>
    **Example:** see `associations_example` under `dython.examples`
<br>
    Parameters
<br>
    ----------
<br>
    df : NumPy ndarray / Pandas DataFrame
<br>
        The data-set for which the features' correlation is computed
<br>
    colcat : string / list / NumPy ndarray
<br>
        Names of columns of the data-set which hold categorical values. Can also be the string 'all' to state that all
<br>
        columns are categorical, or None (default) to state none are categorical
<br>
    mark_columns : Boolean, default = False
<br>
        if True, output's columns' names will have a suffix of '(nom)' or '(con)' based on there type (eda_tools or
<br>
        continuous), as provided by colcat
<br>
    theil_u : Boolean, default = False
<br>
        In the case of categorical-categorical feaures, use Theil's U instead of Cramer's V
<br>
    plot : Boolean, default = True
<br>
        If True, plot a heat-map of the correlation matrix
<br>
    return_results : Boolean, default = False
<br>
        If True, the function will return a Pandas DataFrame of the computed associations
<br>
    kwargs : any key-value pairs
<br>
        Arguments to be passed to used function and methods
<br>
    """
<br>

    <details>

        </summary>
        <ul>
        <li>Args:</li>
        <ul>S,<br>num_factors,<br>lambda_reg = 1e-5,<br>num_iterations = 20,<br>init_std = 0.01,<br>verbose = False,<br>dtype = 'float32',<br>recompute_factors = recompute_factors,<br>*args,<br>**kwargs,<br></ul>
        <li>Docs:<br>    """
<br>
    factorize a given sparse matrix using the Weighted Matrix Factorization algorithm by
<br>
    Hu, Koren and Volinsky.
<br>
    S: 'surplus' confidence matrix, i.e. C - I where C is the matrix with confidence weights.
<br>
        S is sparse while C is not (and the sparsity pattern of S is the same as that of
<br>
        the preference matrix, so it doesn't need to be specified separately).
<br>
    num_factors: the number of factors.
<br>
    lambda_reg: the value of the regularization constant.
<br>
    num_iterations: the number of iterations to run the algorithm for. Each iteration consists
<br>
        of two steps, one to recompute U given V, and one to recompute V given U.
<br>
    init_std: the standard deviation of the Gaussian with which V is initialized.
<br>
    verbose: print a bunch of stuff during training, including timing information.
<br>
    dtype: the dtype of the resulting factor matrices. Using single precision is recommended,
<br>
        it speeds things up a bit.
<br>
    recompute_factors: helper function that implements the inner loop.
<br>
    returns:
<br>
        U, V: factor matrices. If bias=True, the last columns of the matrices contain the biases.
<br>
    """

    >>> mean_reciprocal_rank(rs)
<br>
    0.61111111111111105
<br>
    >>> rs = np.array([[0, 0, 0], [0, 1, 0], [1, 0, 0]])
<br>
    >>> mean_reciprocal_rank(rs)
<br>
    0.5
<br>
    >>> rs = [[0, 0, 0, 1], [1, 0, 0], [1, 0, 0]]
<br>
    >>> mean_reciprocal_rank(rs)
<br>
    0.75
<br>
    Args:
<br>
        rs: Iterator of relevance scores (list or numpy) in rank order
<br>
            (first element is the first item)
<br>
    Returns:
<br>
        Mean reciprocal rank
<br>
    """
<br>

        function | <a name='source/utils/util_metric.py:precision_at_k' href='https://github.com/arita37/dsa2/tree/multi/source/utils/util_metric.py#L61'>precision_at_k</a>
        </summary>
        <ul>
        <li>Args:</li>
        <ul>r,<br>k,<br></ul>
        <li>Docs:<br>    """Score is precision @ k
<br>
    Relevance is binary (nonzero is relevant).
<br>
    >>> r = [0, 0, 1]
<br>
    >>> precision_at_k(r, 1)
<br>
    0.0
<br>
    >>> precision_at_k(r, 2)
<br>
    0.0
<br>
    >>> precision_at_k(r, 3)
<br>
    0.33333333333333331
<br>
    >>> precision_at_k(r, 4)
<br>
    Traceback (most recent call last):
<br>
        File "<stdin>", line 1, in ?
<br>
    ValueError: Relevance score length < k
<br>
    Args:
<br>
        r: Relevance scores (list or numpy) in rank order
<br>
            (first element is the first item)
<br>
    Returns:
<br>
        Precision @ k
<br>
    Raises:
<br>
        ValueError: len(r) must be >= k
<br>
    """
<br>
</li>
        </ul>
    </details>
    <details>
        <summary>
        function | <a name='source/utils/util_metric.py:average_precision' href='https://github.com/arita37/dsa2/tree/multi/source/utils/util_metric.py#L90'>average_precision</a>
        </summary>
        <ul>
        <li>Args:</li>
        <ul>r,<br></ul>
        <li>Docs:<br>    """Score is average precision (area under PR curve)
<br>
    Relevance is binary (nonzero is relevant).
<br>
    >>> r = [1, 1, 0, 1, 0, 1, 0, 0, 0, 1]
<br>
    >>> delta_r = 1. / sum(r)
<br>
    >>> sum([sum(r[:x + 1]) / (x + 1.) * delta_r for x, y in enumerate(r) if y])
<br>
    0.7833333333333333
<br>
    >>> average_precision(r)
<br>
    0.78333333333333333
<br>
    Args:
<br>
        r: Relevance scores (list or numpy) in rank order
<br>
            (first element is the first item)
<br>
    Returns:
<br>
        Average precision
<br>
    """
<br>
</li>
        </ul>
    </details>
    <details>
        <summary>
        function | <a name='source/utils/util_metric.py:mean_average_precision' href='https://github.com/arita37/dsa2/tree/multi/source/utils/util_metric.py#L112'>mean_average_precision</a>
        </summary>
        <ul>
        <li>Args:</li>
        <ul>rs,<br></ul>
        <li>Docs:<br>    """Score is mean average precision

    >>> mean_average_precision(rs)
<br>
    0.78333333333333333
<br>
    >>> rs = [[1, 1, 0, 1, 0, 1, 0, 0, 0, 1], [0]]
<br>
    >>> mean_average_precision(rs)
<br>
    0.39166666666666666

        rs: Iterator of relevance scores (list or numpy) in rank order

        Mean average precision
<br>
    """
<br>
</li>
        </ul>
    </details>
    <details>
        <summary>
        function | <a name='source/utils/util_metric.py:dcg_at_k' href='https://github.com/arita37/dsa2/tree/multi/source/utils/util_metric.py#L130'>dcg_at_k</a>
        </summary>
        <ul>
        <li>Args:</li>
        <ul>r,<br>k,<br>method = 0,<br></ul>
        <li>Docs:<br>    """Score is discounted cumulative gain (dcg)
<br>
    Relevance is positive real values.  Can use binary
<br>
    as the previous methods.
<br>
    Example from
<br>
    http://www.stanford.edu/class/cs276/handouts/EvaluationNew-handout-6-per.pdf
<br>
    >>> r = [3, 2, 3, 0, 0, 1, 2, 2, 3, 0]
<br>
    >>> dcg_at_k(r, 1)
<br>
    3.0
<br>
    >>> dcg_at_k(r, 1, method=1)
<br>
    3.0
<br>
    >>> dcg_at_k(r, 2)
<br>
    5.0
<br>
    >>> dcg_at_k(r, 2, method=1)
<br>
    4.2618595071429155
<br>
    >>> dcg_at_k(r, 10)
<br>
    9.6051177391888114
<br>
    >>> dcg_at_k(r, 11)
<br>
    9.6051177391888114
<br>
    Args:
<br>
        r: Relevance scores (list or numpy) in rank order
<br>
            (first element is the first item)
<br>
        k: Number of results to consider
<br>
        method: If 0 then weights are [1.0, 1.0, 0.6309, 0.5, 0.4307, ...]
<br>
                If 1 then weights are [1.0, 0.6309, 0.5, 0.4307, ...]
<br>
    Returns:
<br>
        Discounted cumulative gain
<br>
    """
<br>
</li>
        </ul>
    </details>

        <summary>

        </summary>
        <ul>
        <li>Args:</li>
        <ul>r,<br>k,<br>method = 0,<br></ul>
        <li>Docs:<br>    """Score is normalized discounted cumulative gain (ndcg)

    >>> r = [3, 2, 3, 0, 0, 1, 2, 2, 3, 0]
<br>
    >>> ndcg_at_k(r, 1)
<br>
    1.0
<br>
    >>> r = [2, 1, 2, 0]
<br>
    >>> ndcg_at_k(r, 4)
<br>
    0.9203032077642922
<br>
    >>> ndcg_at_k(r, 4, method=1)
<br>
    0.96519546960144276
<br>
    >>> ndcg_at_k([0], 1)
<br>
    0.0
<br>
    >>> ndcg_at_k([1], 2)
<br>
    1.0
<br>
    Args:
<br>
        r: Relevance scores (list or numpy) in rank order
<br>
            (first element is the first item)
<br>
        k: Number of results to consider
<br>
        method: If 0 then weights are [1.0, 1.0, 0.6309, 0.5, 0.4307, ...]
<br>
                If 1 then weights are [1.0, 0.6309, 0.5, 0.4307, ...]
<br>
    Returns:
<br>
        Normalized discounted cumulative gain
<br>
    """
<br>

        </ul>

<br>

<br>
csv_path: Path to the CSV file (must be in the current directory) [Required]
<br>
target_field: Target field to predict [Required]
<br>
target_metric: Target metric to optimize [Default: Automatically determined depending on problem type]
<br>
framework: Machine learning framework to use [Default: 'tensorflow']
<br>
config_name: Name of the model (if you want to train models with different names) [Default: 'automl']
<br>
num_trials: Number of trials / different hyperparameter combos to test. [Default: 100]
<br>
split: Train-validation split when training the models [Default: 0.7]
<br>
num_epochs: Number of epochs / passes through the data when training the models. [Default: 20]
<br>
col_types: Dictionary of fields:data types to use to override automl-gs's guesses. (only when using in Python) [Default: {}]
<br>
gpu: For non-Tensorflow frameworks and Pascal-or-later GPUs, boolean to determine whether to use GPU-optimized training methods (TensorFlow can detect it automatically) [Default: False]
<br>
tpu_address: For TensorFlow, hardware address of the TPU on the system. [Default: None]   
<br>

<br>
   The output of the automl-gs training is:
<br>

<br>
A timestamped folder (e.g. automl_tensorflow_20190317_020434) with contains:
<br>
model.py: The generated model file.
<br>
pipeline.py: The generated pipeline file.
<br>
requirements.txt: The generated requirements file.
<br>
/encoders: A folder containing JSON-serialized encoder files
<br>
/metadata: A folder containing training statistics + other cool stuff not yet implemented!
<br>
The model itself (format depends on framework)
<br>
automl_results.csv: A CSV containing the training results after each epoch and the hyperparameters used to train at that time.
<br>
Once the training is done, you can run the generated files from the command line within the generated folder above.

<br>
def pd_generic_transform(df, col=None, pars={}, model=None)  :
<br>
 
<br>
     Transform or Samples using  model.fit()   model.sample()  or model.transform()
<br>
    params:
<br>
            df    : (pandas dataframe) original dataframe
<br>
            col   : column name for data enancement
<br>
            pars  : (dict - optional) contains:                                          
<br>
                path_model_save: saving location if save_model is set to True
<br>
                path_model_load: saved model location to skip training
<br>
                path_data_new  : new data where saved 
<br>
    returns:
<br>
            model, df_new, col, pars
<br>
   
<br>
    path_model_save = pars.get('path_model_save', 'data/output/ztmp/')
<br>
    pars_model      = pars.get('pars_model', {} )
<br>
    model_method    = pars.get('method', 'transform')
<br>
    
<br>
    # model fitting 
<br>
    if 'path_model_load' in pars:
<br>
            model = load(pars['path_model_load'])
<br>
    else:
<br>
            log('##### Training Started #####')
<br>
            model = model( **pars_model)
<br>
            model.fit(df)
<br>
            log('##### Training Finshed #####')
<br>
            try:
<br>
                 save(model, path_model_save )
<br>
                 log('model saved at: ' + path_model_save  )
<br>
            except:
<br>
                 log('saving model failed: ', path_model_save)
<br>

<br>
    log('##### Generating Samples/transform #############')    
<br>
    if model_method == 'sample' :
<br>
        n_samples =pars.get('n_samples', max(1, 0.10 * len(df) ) )
<br>
        new_data  = model.sample(n_samples)
<br>
        
<br>
    elif model_method == 'transform' :
<br>
        new_data = model.transform(df.values)
<br>
    else :
<br>
        raise Exception("Unknown", model_method)
<br>
        
<br>
    log_pd( new_data, n=7)    
<br>
    if 'path_newdata' in pars :
<br>
        new_data.to_parquet( pars['path_newdata'] + '/features.parquet' ) 
<br>
        log('###### df transform save on disk', pars['path_newdata'] )    
<br>
    
<br>
    return model, df_new, col, pars
<br>

<br>

        </summary>
        <ul>

    </details>
    <details>
        <summary>
        function | <a name='data/docs/features/feature_cleaning/outlier.py:outlier_detect_IQR' href='https://github.com/arita37/dsa2/tree/multi/data/docs/features/feature_cleaning/outlier.py#L21'>outlier_detect_IQR</a>
        </summary>
        <ul>
        <li>Args:</li>
        <ul>data,<br>col,<br>threshold = 3,<br></ul>
        <li>Docs:<br>    '''
<br>
    outlier detection by Interquartile Ranges Rule, also known as Tukey's test. 
<br>
    calculate the IQR ( 75th quantile - 25th quantile) 
<br>
    and the 25th 75th quantile. 
<br>
    Any value beyond:
<br>
        upper bound = 75th quantile + （IQR * threshold）
<br>
        lower bound = 25th quantile - （IQR * threshold）   
<br>
    are regarded as outliers. Default threshold is 3.
<br>
    '''
<br>
</li>
        </ul>
    </details>
    <details>
        <summary>
        function | <a name='data/docs/features/feature_cleaning/outlier.py:outlier_detect_mean_std' href='https://github.com/arita37/dsa2/tree/multi/data/docs/features/feature_cleaning/outlier.py#L43'>outlier_detect_mean_std</a>
        </summary>
        <ul>
        <li>Args:</li>
        <ul>data,<br>col,<br>threshold = 3,<br></ul>
        <li>Docs:<br>    '''
<br>
    outlier detection by Mean and Standard Deviation Method.
<br>
    If a value is a certain number(called threshold) of standard deviations away 
<br>
    from the mean, that data point is identified as an outlier. 
<br>
    Default threshold is 3.
<br>

<br>
    This method can fail to detect outliers because the outliers increase the standard deviation. 
<br>
    The more extreme the outlier, the more the standard deviation is affected.
<br>
    '''
<br>
</li>
        </ul>
    </details>
    <details>
        <summary>
        function | <a name='data/docs/features/feature_cleaning/outlier.py:outlier_detect_MAD' href='https://github.com/arita37/dsa2/tree/multi/data/docs/features/feature_cleaning/outlier.py#L64'>outlier_detect_MAD</a>
        </summary>
        <ul>
        <li>Args:</li>
        <ul>data,<br>col,<br>threshold = 3.5,<br></ul>
        <li>Docs:<br>    """
<br>
    outlier detection by Median and Median Absolute Deviation Method (MAD)
<br>
    The median of the residuals is calculated. Then, the difference is calculated between each historical value and this median. 
<br>
    These differences are expressed as their absolute values, and a new median is calculated and multiplied by 
<br>
    an empirically derived constant to yield the median absolute deviation (MAD). 
<br>
    If a value is a certain number of MAD away from the median of the residuals, 
<br>
    that value is classified as an outlier. The default threshold is 3 MAD.
<br>
    
<br>
    This method is generally more effective than the mean and standard deviation method for detecting outliers, 
<br>
    but it can be too aggressive in classifying values that are not really extremely different. 
<br>
    Also, if more than 50% of the data points have the same value, MAD is computed to be 0, 
<br>
    so any value different from the residual median is classified as an outlier.
<br>
    """
<br>
</li>
        </ul>
    </details>

<br>

<br>

    #To obtain a latent representation of the training data:

    latent_data = autoencoder.encode(data)
<br>

<br>
    #To decode the latent representation:
<br>
    reconstructed_data = autoencoder.decode(latent_data)
<br>

<br>
    #Encoding and decoding can also be merged into the following single statement:
<br>
    reconstructed_data = autoencoder.predict(data)
<br>

<br>
    :return:
<br>
    """
